{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17584888","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17584888"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:28+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T07:59:28+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14824"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14824","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14824"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7515"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79586"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7515","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7515"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14824"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64890"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"7647"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18372"},{"type":"contributions","id":"27213"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79586","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/79586"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EMeiosis is a key process of the germ cells which results in the production of gametes. Meiosis I is the first meiotic division and meiosis II the second. During meiosis I, there are a number of processes which result in a reduction of chromosome number.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes what occurs during meiosis I?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Chromosomes align at the metaphase plate in a single row","Crossing over occurs between sister chromatids","Four haploid cells are produced","Homologous chromosomes separate to opposite poles","Prophase includes DNA replication"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EDuring meiosis I, \u003Cstrong\u003Ehomologous chromosomes separate to opposite poles\u003C/strong\u003E while sister chromatids remain together. This is a key distinguishing feature from mitosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDNA replication\u003C/strong\u003E occurs during interphase before meiosis begins, not during prophase I. During prophase I, homologous chromosomes pair up (synapsis) and crossing over occurs.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChromosomes align\u003C/strong\u003E at the metaphase plate as tetrads (pairs of homologous chromosomes) during metaphase I, not in a single row.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECrossing over\u003C/strong\u003E occurs between homologous chromosomes, not between sister chromatids. This process creates genetic diversity through recombination.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMeiosis I produces two haploid cells, not \u003Cstrong\u003Efour haploid cells\u003C/strong\u003E. The formation of four haploid cells occurs only after completion of both meiosis I and meiosis II.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Meiosis I separates homologous chromosomes while maintaining sister chromatids together.","Prophase I involves synapsis and crossing over between homologous chromosomes.","The end result of Meiosis I is two haploid cells with replicated chromosomes."],"references":["Alberts B, Bray D, Johnson A, Lewis J, Raff M, Roberts K, et al. Cell communities: tissues, stem cells, and cancer. Essential cell biology, 4th New York Edition: Garland Science; 2018.","Tortora GJ, Derrickson BH, Burkett B, Peoples G, Dye D, Cooke J, et al. Principles of Anatomy and Physiology, 2nd Asia-Pacific Edition: John Wiley \u0026 Sons, Limited; 2019."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64890"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14824"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"64890","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/64890"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-15T10:00:04+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-15T10:00:54+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7515"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"79586"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/4940"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udee7","name":"Cell Biology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":"2024-10-17T23:16:52+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-31T13:16:21+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"14"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4947","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.